Add macaroons support to node.js bindings

Patch-By:  William Whitacre <numayacto@gmail.com>

Patch against HyperDex 1.8.1 Source Distribution
Source : http://hyperdex.org/src/hyperdex-1.8.1.tar.gz
Patch  : ./hyperdex-1.8.1-authjs.patch

Patch for enabling node.js bindings for authorization support and test program.

Successfully tested against node.js versions

node@0.10.36 (npm@1.3.6)
node@0.10.40 (npm@1.4.28)

Test program depends on
node-hyperdex-test@0.0.0 /home/ww/s/node-hyperdex-test
├─┬ macaroons.js@0.3.5
│ ├── ecma-nacl@2.2.0
│ └─┬ typedarray-to-buffer@3.0.4
│   └── is-typedarray@1.0.0
└── when@3.7.3

No support for `secret` argument. Directly pass attribute `__secret` instead to
create a secret record:

    c.put('space', 'key', { __secret: 'super secret', ... }, put_callback);

Supports `auth` argument in the following form:

    c.get('space', 'key', [ M.serialize() ], get_callback);

Note that the tail of the argument list after method specific arguments was
before taken to just always be the callback. With this patch, existing code will
not break, but instead if there are two extra arguments, then the first is taken
to be an array of tokens, and the second is taken to be a callback.

Use an anonymous BusyBee ID for the HyperDex client

The ID generation was not robust enough to be safe when launching hundreds of
clients simultaneously, occasionally leading to clients with duplicate IDs.
This would lead one of the two clients to hang, as its replies would get sent to
the other by any daemons to which they both connected.

Reorder library link order.

For the static build, the link order matters.  Linking B before A when A links
B's symbols ended up with many errors about symbols that were not found.  Change
the link order so that A->B implies A comes before B on the linker cmd line.

A bunch of fixes.

 - Expose transfers using a stable sort, so once exposed a transfer will forever
   remain exposed.
 - Issue a new configuration if checkpoints seem stuck (should never happen
   anymore, but this is a safety measure just in case).

Ensure daemons always finish checkpoints.

Under heavy reconfiguration activity, a daemon could drop a checkpoint until
either reconfiguration (again), or a USR2 debug signal was sent.
Expose a subset of transfers at a time
Update YCSB to not abort on reconfigure

Fix a segfault in previous commit (caught by testing).

For spaces with subspaces, or when performing transfers, it assumed an entry
would be in a map when, in fact, it was not.  This would lead to a NULL ptr
dereference.  Caught by the replication-stress-test.

Aggressively update in-memory version numbers

A large version number to issue is stored on disk, and a copy is cached in
memory.  This patch aggressively updates that copy on writes.  The practical
upshot should be that checkpoints converge significantly faster than they would
otherwise.

Another big patch going back 2 months to pre-NSDI crunch

Here's what it contains:

 - Automatically scale a cluster as nodes are added
 - Improve time-to-recovery when a node goes offline for a short time
 - Improved the admin library with human-readable error messages
 - Improved the coordinator-daemon coupling to be more robust
 - Enable nodes to go offline without contacting the coordinator at all
 - Add barriers to track stability.  All ops initiated before the barrier starts
   will be complete on the other side of the barrier.
 - Use raw LaTeX for documentation.
 - Fix a bunch of bugs
 - Add warning messages for when a daemon is brought online with a different
   coordinator.
 - Improved efficiency of internal state tracking.

Localized primary and secondary indices.

This commit expands support for indexing data on each machine.  Through the
primary_index and secondary_index keywords, user can instruct HyperDex to add
indices on structures that are not used for subspace attributes.

For example, the following space indexes the elements of a set:

    space kv key k attribute map(string, string) v primary_index v.

Fix a deadlock between background and network threads.

We paused the background threads by holding a lock across reconfiguration.
Unfortunately, we did so by first blocking the threads and then the network
traffic.  If a packet arrived that required passing info to the background
threads (by holding their lock), we could deadlock.  Fix this by adding another
set of condition variables between the background threads and the thread that
performs reconfiguration.

Start capturing the moment we could see data

Previously:  capture after xfer-go-live was invoked
Now:  capture from the moment the transfer begins
Rationale:  Consider chain X->Y->Z.  If all three start capture C, and X departs
    the region provably after Y and Z started the capture, then X can rejoin
    using only C and nothing else.  This takes the transfer from sizeof(data) +
    sizeof(delta) to just sizeof(delta).

Maintain the layout as servers fail and join.

to maximize the fault tolerance of each region.

ASSUMES: - There is always at least one server in each region.
         - Servers come back on alternate IPs.

Two-phase shutdown of a single node.

On ^C, a server does the following:

1.  Inform the coordinator that it is shutting down.
2.  Wait for all nodes to adopt the latest configuration.
3.  Inform the coordinator that it exiting

At the end of this, the coordinator has been given an opportunity to
disseminate a new config to everyone before the single node exits.

Harden the shutdown of a single daemon.

LevelDB requires that a database outlive its snapshots, which in turn must
outlive their iterators.  This change enforces this across the code by keeping
our own reference counts to ensure that no matter what order we shutdown, we do
shutdown cleanly.  A segfault leaves LevelDB in a less-nice place than a clean
shutdown, making future startup hard.

Automate the transfer process from beginning to end

When "initiate-transfer" is called, the tail of the region sends all state to
the new node.  Once all state is sent, the coordinator is asked to make the
transfer "live" by appending the node to the end of the region's chain.
Finally, once all state is transferred, the tail node is made a full member of
the chain and the transfer is complete.

from key hashes onto log ids and is much faster than a normal hash table.

Massively refactor the datatypes code.

This change does several things:
 - Move the code concerning datatypes to datatypes/.  Both the client and server
   can use this code.
 - Clients now perform much more validation.  The server ALWAYS validated
   everything, but would throw an uninformative error.  Now the client will
   always check first, and can return an informative error based on that check.
   This reduces the server's burden.
 - Automatic type coercion is easier to follow.  There are straightforward cases
   for when an empty "generic" set can be converted to any other set and it
   does not rely upon the ad-hoc, per-type rules that existed before.

Include key size in calculations of microop sizes.

An OP_INT64_ADD may be for a map or a normal number.  In the former
case, we'd neglect the key size, and corrupt memory.

We fix this by pessimistically assuming the worst for every map op.
This will be faster, but allocate slightly more memory than is strictly
necessary.

A fuzz tester for datastructures.

This fuzz tester performs random operations on HyperDex, and verifies that
HyperDex performs as expected.  It models HyperDex using Python's
datastructures, and ensures that HyperDex's datastructures closely follow
Python's.

Improve the Python client's datastructures code

There were a few things that were surprising, e.g. returning False when an
object didn't exist rather than raising NOTFOUND.

This is part of the push to improve the datastructures code and fixes #35.

Detect error conditions after reading from sockets

This change is in the hypercoordinator main loop.

Add support for detecting overflow for math ops

When using atomic_add or other math variants, overflow was treated the same way
that C treated it:  undefined behavior.  With this commit, we fully define
overflow:  it'll make raise an error.  Furthermore, we adopt Python's convention
of truncating towards negative infinity for the reasons expressed in [1].

1.  http://python-history.blogspot.com/2010/08/why-pythons-integer-division-floors.html
Remove w_ from a function name.

Only return SUCCESS for atomic_* if the object exists

Previously, an empty set of objects would succeed no matter what, even if the
object did not exist.  Now when an atomic_* (or similar) is attempted without
specifying any changes, it will succeed only if the object already exists.

Allow empty variations of list/set/map.

Previously, empty versions of list/set/map would cause "WRONG_TYPE"
errors.  Now, they are perfectly permissible.

mask would be 0.  When searching, it would then match anything, regardless of
the mask.  When sectors split in four, the set with the bit set would be matched
when the others should have been matched.

Python API: map_atomic_xxx() fix.

Setup:

space phonebook
dimensions username, first, last, phone (map (string, int64))
key username auto 1 3
subspace first, last auto 2 3

Symtom:
python

Python 2.7.2 (default, Oct 27 2011, 01:40:22)
[GCC 4.6.1 20111003 (Red Hat 4.6.1-10)] on linux2
Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
>>> import hyperclient
>>> c = hyperclient.Client('127.0.0.1', 1234)
>>> c.put('phonebook', 'jsmith1', {'first': 'John', 'last': 'Smith',
>>> 'phone': {'home': 4165551024, 'work': 4165551025, 'other':
>>> 4165551026}})
True
>>> c.get('phonebook', 'jsmith1')
{'phone': {'home': 4165551024, 'work': 4165551025, 'other': 4165551026},
'last': 'Smith', 'first': 'John'}
>>> c.map_atomic_add('phonebook', 'jsmith1', {'phone': {'home': 10,
>>> 'work': 100, 'other': 1000}})
True
>>> c.get('phonebook', 'jsmith1')
{'phone': {'home': 4165551034, 'work': 4165551025, 'other': 4165551026},
'last': 'Smith', 'first': 'John'}
>>>

Expected the last c.get(), above, to return:
{'phone': {'home': 4165551034, 'work': 4165551125, 'other': 4165552026},
'last': 'Smith', 'first': 'John'}

To wit, each phone number (home,work,other) should have been incremented
by (10,100,1000) repectively. But, clearly, only the first 'home' number
was incremented by 10. The rest were untouched.

This commit fixes the problem.

Safely handle only strings and numbers in java API

As we now have more than just strings and numbers for
datatypes, I made the java API safely deal with only

Remove stupidity in the microop structure.

For convenience, I had one pair of args for each primitive data type.
This made it convenient to serialize/unserialize, but also added some
special-case behavior to the datastructues code.  Furthermore, if one
were to add another primitive data type, one would need to expand the
microop structure.

By making the structure smaller, we cut some corner cases, and make
things simpler.

Working maps as HyperDex types.

Maps may use strings or integers as the key or value respectively.

For every operation that may be performed on the value (when not in a map),
there is a "map_*" variant that operates on the map's value.

Known Bugs:
 - The append/prepend methods of strings blow up by not serializing correctly.
   Fix:  Figure out where the serializing problem is.
 - If the requested operation translates to more than one micro op, then there
   is a large chance that the ops will be rejected because they are not sorted
   correctly.
   Fix:  Pack the ops into the message in sorted order.
Inline the apply_set_${op}_${type} functions.
Move close/err processing to after read/write.

Some endianness fixups.

e provides several convenient, portable conversion routines that are
faster than memmove + convert.  An upside of using these routines is
improved compatibility with CentOS5.

Fix warnings in hyperdaemon/physical.cc

They stemmed from a failure to call work_close (and thus, there were
unused variables.

Have just one datatype enum.

There was one enum maintained for the client, and one for everything else.  They
didn't have to agree, and there was a lot of useless translation between the
two.  This patch merges them into one common enum, shaving some useless code.

Remove buffer usage in the hyperspacehashing lib.

Buffers are heavyweight and memory-owning.  In order to pass the key or
value to an object, a new buffer had to be created, and the contents
copied.  This buffer could be passed by reference into the hashing
layer, but the damage of a memory allocation/copy was already done.

This patch uses the new e "slice" object which refers to memory in a
lightweight, non-memory-owning manner.  The rest of the app (built on
hsh) can now follow this pattern.

The reason for this change was simple:  For a single key and value,
there were, on average, 14 buffer copies per operation, all of which are
unnecessary.  As this change percolates up the code base, it will
eliminate all of these useless operations.  The result will be reduced
CPU usage (right now, a number of clients can saturate one host's CPU).

Banish libev.
Completely remove masterlink.
Don't fail poll on EINTR.

Occasionally a message would be double-sent.

This would confuse the client, and tests failed as a result.
The fix is two-fold:

1)  Do not double-send messages.  This was achieved by locking an
    existing mutex in a second location.  (this commit)
2)  Make the client more robust by acting on messages it is expecting.
    This will involve tracking nonces.  (future commits)

For now, the first fix removes the problem (the second just masks
symptoms, but is good for robust code).

Don't block in work_accept.

If multiple threads woke up from poll and went to accept, the could wait
forever in the work_accept function.
Ensure that threads pause eventually.
Use an event-loop-free coordinatorlink.

Change the network recv model.

Before N network worker threads would wait on a queue for messages to be
pushed.  In busy times this would lead to all threads pulling messages
from the e::lockfree_fifo.  Unfortunately, it takes many clients to put
such a load on the queue.  During less busy times (e.g., not loaded to
capacity), threads wait on a condition variable, and each push to the
queue ends up causing a lock/signal/unlock.  This also tends to have a
thread do a send, push a message (for self delivery), and then wake
another thread.  By the time the pushing thread gets back around to
popping, the other thread has woken, and taken over the message.

Under the new model, all threads enter a loop where they perform a
poll(2) and react to events.  It seems to eliminates almost all latency
associated with the delivery queue.  Furthermore, threads which
self-deliver are likely to pop the same message they push, so costs of
transferring data between cores is significantly reduced.  I measure a
94.22% performance improvement in latency.  My only concern is whether
poll will actually multiplex between threads.

Stop-the-world reconfiguration.

There is a critical section in which we can safely assert that network

guarantees that any messages processed after it will use the new
configuration for every step of the processing for the message (this is
just one state transition for the whole update -- it is entirely
possible that a message is marked pending under the old configuration,
but acknowledged under the new configuration.

Add a method to pause the receipt of messages.

A pause/unpause pair will block/unblock threads that try to receive
messages.  By waiting until all network threads become blocked on the
communication layer, we may confidently change configuration between
epochs without worrying about straggling threads acting on messages
received before the new configuration, but with a replication or data
layer operating after the new configuration.  I cannot prove that such a
scenario would be problematic (as most of these other layers make sanity
checks of their own), but then again the cost of doing so is not much,
not incurred very often, and trivial compared to my cost of thinking
about it.

Yay!  We have linearizability!

Up until this point our replication scheme didn't provide
linearizability in the case of point-leader failures.

The specific case we had trouble with was:
1.  The last replica in subspace n-1 sends an update message to the
    point leader.
2.  The point leader sends ACK to client.
3.  The point leader dies and the client message is not lost.  The
    second replica in subspace 0 becomes a point leader, and has no clue
    that the message was acknowledged.
4.  The client sends a get to the new point leader and sees a break from
    our linearizability guarantees.

The fix:  After sending to all replicas in all subspaces, extra PENDING
message[1] is sent in reverse along the entire subspace 0 chain,
starting at the last replica and working toward the point-leader.  The
point leader may commit/ack the client when it receives this message,
and may then send the ACK message as it did before.

Add special functions to the messaging layer.

The special (e.g., not entity to entity) functions take extra parameters
to determine the entity to which (or from which) a message is sent.  For
example, if we know that we must send an ACK from a region, we can just
send(region, ...) and let the communication layer sort out the proper
entity which fits as the source (or it drops the message).  The three
special functions are:

 - forward in chain A, or to the head of B
 - forward in chain A, or to the tail of B
 - backward in chain A, or to the tail of B

These replace the ad-hoc variations of these, and make it easier to
understand exactly where a message will go (the ability to send to head
or tail of B when sending forward in a chain was prompted by the
upcoming change referred to in the previous commit RE: PENDING).

Add a PENDING message type.

A PENDING message is sent along the point leader's chain in reverse.  It
signals that a PUT or DEL is now pending on every node that it must
touch and is waiting for an ACK from the point leader.  The receipt of
this message type indicates that a host must (TODO) mark the message as
such so that if the host becomes point-leader, it can immediately
commit/ACK the message so that the client does not see a prefix of the
true history.

Found the bug that caused the occasional NOTFOUND.

The 'count' client issues alternating PUT/GET requests for keys.  By the
guarantees of linearizability, we know that the GET should ALWAYS return
the PUT.  This was not the case.  It happened ~1/1000 times with the
default disk-flushing timeouts, and more often with more aggressive
timings.

The problem:  For certain keys, if the key was put to disk, it would be
dropped because the network-exposed regions created disks with the same
prefix/mask.  This is incorrect because network-exposed regions'
coordinates are created solely by the dimensions which form the region's
subspace, while the on-disk regions are formed using all dimensions.
Thus, it was incorrect to use the same region for both.  The solution is
to use a region of (X, Y, 0, 0) instead, as it will capture all elements
from the network region.

Create a single disk which has fast get/search.

GET on average requires reading one memory page from disk + the contents
of the query.

SEARCH requires reading < 12MB to figure out where else to read to
satisfy queries.  Search must be done in an iterative fashion (e.g., you
cannot read all from disk at once and cache in memory or try to blast
over the network).  Creating an iterator to the disk is a pointer copy,
integer copy, and atomic increment.  Iterating disk requires reading a
portion of the 12MB, and then has the cost of a GET.
